Sequence analysis of Persuasion Data

This is built upon Erikas work. Using the TraMineR package for sequence analysis. The first part is analysis of persuaders sequences.

#install.packages("TraMineR")

Load the data. And plot the frequencies of different states at each step, comparing the donated and not donated groups.

persuader <- read.csv("persuaderOnly.csv", stringsAsFactors = F)
persuader.alphab <- c("emo", "log", "cre", "pro","task", "other")
persuader.seq <- seqdef(persuader, 3:12, xtstep = 6, alphabet = persuader.alphab)
##  [>] 6 distinct states appear in the data:
##      1 = cre
##      2 = emo
##      3 = log
##      4 = other
##      5 = pro
##      6 = task
##  [>] state coding:
##        [alphabet]  [label]  [long label]
##      1  emo         emo      emo
##      2  log         log      log
##      3  cre         cre      cre
##      4  pro         pro      pro
##      5  task        task     task
##      6  other       other    other
##  [>] 652 sequences in the data set
##  [>] min/max sequence length: 10/10
donate.seq <- seqdef(persuader %>% filter(persuader$donate_p==1), 3:12, xtstep = 6, alphabet = persuader.alphab)
##  [>] 6 distinct states appear in the data:
##      1 = cre
##      2 = emo
##      3 = log
##      4 = other
##      5 = pro
##      6 = task
##  [>] state coding:
##        [alphabet]  [label]  [long label]
##      1  emo         emo      emo
##      2  log         log      log
##      3  cre         cre      cre
##      4  pro         pro      pro
##      5  task        task     task
##      6  other       other    other
##  [>] 362 sequences in the data set
##  [>] min/max sequence length: 10/10
notdonate.seq <- seqdef(persuader %>% filter(persuader$donate_p==0), 3:12, xtstep = 6, alphabet = persuader.alphab)
##  [>] 6 distinct states appear in the data:
##      1 = cre
##      2 = emo
##      3 = log

##  [>] 290 sequences in the data set
##  [>] min/max sequence length: 10/10
seqdplot(persuader.seq, group = persuader$donate_p, border = NA)

Now, we need to analyse the subsequences of these groups.

#transition <- seqetm(persuader.seq, method = "transition")
#transition
pder.seqe <- seqecreate(persuader.seq)
pder.seqestate <- seqecreate(persuader.seq, tevent = "state")
pder.seqeperiod <- seqecreate(persuader.seq, tevent = "period")
#pder.seqe[1]
#pder.seqestate[1]
#pder.seqeperiod[1]

don.seqe <- seqecreate(donate.seq)
don.seqestate <- seqecreate(donate.seq, tevent = "state")
don.seqeperiod <- seqecreate(donate.seq, tevent = "period")

ndon.seqe <- seqecreate(notdonate.seq)
ndon.seqestate <- seqecreate(notdonate.seq, tevent = "state")
ndon.seqeperiod <- seqecreate(notdonate.seq, tevent = "period")

Now we have some event sequences, we try to find the frequent subsequences. There are three types of sequences, here I put two: transition subsequences and state subsequences.

The transition subsequences are:

donsub <- seqefsub(don.seqe, min.support = 50, constraint = seqeconstraint(count.method = 2 ))
plot(donsub)

donsub <- seqefsub(don.seqe, min.support = 20, constraint = seqeconstraint(max.gap = 3, window.size = 8, count.method = 2 ))
plot(donsub)

The state subsequences are:

donsubstate <- seqefsub(don.seqestate, min.support = 100, constraint = seqeconstraint(count.method = 2 ))
plot(donsubstate)

donsubstate <- seqefsub(don.seqestate, min.support = 50, constraint = seqeconstraint(max.gap = 3, window.size = 8, count.method = 2 ))
plot(donsubstate)

There is also another function to compare subsequence frenquencies from two groups. However, there are two methods to calculate, and I dont know what they are exactly. But the Chi-square test is less strict than the other one Bonferroni test.

pdersubseq <- seqefsub(pder.seqestate, min.support = 10, constraint = seqeconstraint(count.method = 2 ))
cohort <- factor(persuader$donate_p > 0, labels = c("no donation", "donation"))
discrcohort <- seqecmpgroup(pdersubseq, group = cohort, method = "chisq")
plot(discrcohort[1:20])

pdersubseq <- seqefsub(pder.seqe, min.support = 10, constraint = seqeconstraint(count.method = 2 ))
cohort <- factor(persuader$donate_p > 0, labels = c("no donation", "donation"))
discrcohort <- seqecmpgroup(pdersubseq, group = cohort, method = "chisq")
plot(discrcohort[1:20])
